Bakrie & Brothers, Garuda, Jasa Marga: Indonesia Equity Preview

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-07-28T01:44:23Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-28/bakrie-brothers-garuda-jasa-marga-indonesia-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are
in parentheses, and share prices are as of the previous close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  rose 1 percent to 4,174.11.  Banks: Indonesia’s commercial lending may rise as much as
25 percent, more than last year’s 23 percent growth and higher
than the central bank’s 2011 estimate of 24 percent, as slowing
consumer prices allow policy makers to hold borrowing costs at a
near-record low, PT Bank Central Asia (BBCA IJ) President
Director Jahja Setiaatmadja said in an interview.  Bank Central Asia, the nation’s biggest bank by market
value, climbed 0.6 percent to 8,350 rupiah and PT Bank Mandiri
(BMRI IJ), the largest by assets, rose 2.6 percent to 8,050
rupiah.  Energy companies: Crude oil futures dropped 2.2 percent to
$97.40 a barrel in  New York  yesterday, the lowest settlement
since July 18. Oil was last at $96.96 in after-hours trading.  PT Medco Energi Internasional (MEDC IJ),  Indonesia ’s
biggest listed oil company, gained 2 percent to 2,550 rupiah, PT
Benakat Petroleum Energy (BIPI IJ), fell 1 percent to 102
rupiah.  PT Bakrie & Brothers (BNBR IJ): The  investment company 
plans to form a unit that may raise and manage between $200
million to $300 million for infrastructure projects, including
 power plants  and toll roads, Investor Daily Indonesia reported,
citing President Director Bobby Gafur Umar. Bakrie & Brothers
declined 1.4 percent to 73 rupiah.  PT Garuda Indonesia (GIAA IJ): The airline’s flights to
domestic and international destinations, including Solo in
Central Java and  Tokyo , were operating normally this morning
even though there is a strike by the pilots union, Pujobroto, a
spokesman at the carrier said in an e-mailed statement. Garuda,
Indonesia’s biggest airline, fell 1.9 percent to 510 rupiah.  PT Jasa Marga (JSMR IJ): The company’s first-half net
income rose to 751.57 billion rupiah ($88 million) from 647.64
billion rupiah a year earlier, Indonesia’s biggest toll-road
operator said in a statement published in  Bisnis Indonesia . Jasa
Marga climbed 0.6 percent to 3,950 rupiah.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at   dboey@bloomberg.net  